Hypothesis 1: Do More Friends Lead to More Happiness?

friends_vs_happiness <- responses %>%
  select(Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>%
  arrange(desc(Number.of.friends))
xyplot( Number.of.friends ~ Happiness.in.life, data = friends_vs_happiness, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE)

The majority of people had an average number of friends and happiness in life where they rated both values as 3. However, the correlation between friends and happiness was left skewed, with more people having a higher level of happiness and friends. We expected those with more friends to be generally happier, and the results agreed with this prediction.

Hypothesis 2: Does Gender Relate to Happiness Among Slovakian Youth?

gender_vs_happiness <- responses %>%
    select(Gender, Happiness.in.life)
#mplot(gender_vs_happiness)
 bwplot( Happiness.in.life ~ Gender, data = gender_vs_happiness, main="")

There seemed to be no correlation between gender and happiness among Slovakian youth.

Hypothesis 3: What About Happiness and Age?

happiness_vs_age <- responses %>%
  na.omit(NA) %>%
  select(Age, Happiness.in.life) %>%
  group_by(Age) %>%
  summarise(avg_happiness = mean(Happiness.in.life))
#mplot(happiness_vs_age)
xyplot( avg_happiness ~ Age, data = happiness_vs_age, main="")

There is a slight correlation between age and happiness, as people seem to become slightly happier the older they are.

Hypothesis 4: Are Religion and Happiness Related?

religion_vs_happiness <- responses %>%
  na.omit(NA) %>%
  select(Religion, Happiness.in.life)
#mplot(religion_vs_happiness)
 xyplot( Religion ~ Happiness.in.life, data = religion_vs_happiness, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE)

There was a general negative correlation between religion and happiness in life. A majority of people who ranked themsleves as not interested in religion (1 and 2) were generally happy. #Hypothesis 5: Do Smokers Play Soccer?

smoking_vs_sports <- responses %>%
  na.omit(NA)%>%
  select(Passive.sport, Smoking) %>%
  group_by(Smoking) %>%
  summarise(avg_sports = mean(Passive.sport))%>%
  arrange(desc(avg_sports))
#mplot(smoking_vs_sports)
bwplot( avg_sports ~ Smoking, data = smoking_vs_sports, panel=panel.violin, main="")

We hypothesized that people who had more experience smoking would have less interest in sports and other leisure activities. According to our chart, those who had never smoked had a greater interest in sports and current smokers had the least. So we were correct!

Hypothesis 6: Are Only Children Lonely Children?

lonely_vs_only <- responses %>%
  na.omit(NA) %>%
  select(Only.child, Loneliness)
#mplot(lonely_vs_only)
bwplot( Loneliness ~ Only.child, data = lonely_vs_only, main="")

We are both only children, and based on our experiences, we hypothesized that only children would not be particularly lonely because they are accustomed to being alone. Our results indicate that only children and those with siblings have the same distribution of loneliness.
